cks_track_name\', favour_sources, source_preferences=[\'lastfm\',\'musicbrainz\',\'discogs\'])",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "For this list-like attribute, the available evidence points to source ordering rather than union/intersection. lastfm is the strongest source against validation, so favour_sources with lastfm first is the closest supported resolver under frozen infrastructure. shortest_string is the recommended conceptual rule from the source-vs-validation comparison, but for list-valued track names that may not apply directly in PyDI fusion the way it does for scalar album name. union would likely worsen exact-list evaluation by adding extras; intersection would drop legitimate tracks; current musicbrainz-first ordering is contradicted by the probe.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.09\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "name",\n      "issue": "Current shortest_string resolver is already aligned with source-vs-validation evidence (lastfm best, shortest_string recommended), but source trust/order is not explicit.",\n      "fix": "Preserve shortest_string for \'name\'; do not change this protected-near-protected attribute unless implementing a global trust cleanup elsewhere.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "The diagnostics already recommend shortest_string and current accuracy is 78.3%, close to its observed ceiling. Changing to voting or prefer_higher_trust risks regression because validation often prefers concise canonical titles. This attribute should be preserved.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "artist",\n      "issue": "Current resolver longest_string is inconsistent with evidence showing musicbrainz exact 83% and recommendation prefer_higher_trust(musicbrainz > discogs > lastfm).",\n      "fix": "Use strategy.add_attribute_fuser(\'artist\', prefer_higher_trust, trust_map={\'musicbrainz\': 3, \'discogs\': 2, \'lastfm\': 1})",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "A single source is clearly best. longest_string can over-select embellished artist strings like collaborations or aliases, whereas validation aligns most closely with musicbrainz. voting may be harmed by disagreement across stylings; favour_sources would work but explicit trust is clearer and consistent with the probe.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.03\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "duration",\n      "issue": "Current resolver maximum conflicts with evidence recommending prefer_higher_trust with discogs best exact rate (46%) and musicbrainz best fuzzy but 0 exact. Maximum may systematically overestimate when sources disagree.",\n      "fix": "Use strategy.add_attribute_fuser(\'duration\', prefer_higher_trust, trust_map={\'discogs\': 3, \'musicbrainz\': 2, \'lastfm\': 1})",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "For scalar numeric duration, maximum is only correct if validation reflects a complete aggregate; the probe does not support that. Source comparison explicitly recommends prefer_higher_trust with discogs first. median was considered but no evidence indicates symmetric numeric noise; maximum is already likely causing overshoots; favour_sources is a weaker version of trust-based choice.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.03\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "post_clustering",\n      "issue": "Ambiguous many-to-many correspondences are likely contributing to empty/wrong fused records; cluster analysis explicitly recommends MaximumBipartiteMatching.",\n      "fix": "Enable post-clustering with MaximumBipartiteMatching before fusion over the frozen correspondence sets.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "This directly addresses ambiguous clusters without changing blocking or matching. Given one-to-many ratio 20.4% and ambiguity ratio 87.6% in discogs_lastfm, enforcing a one-to-one resolution should improve which records are fused together and reduce missing_fused values. StableMatching or GreedyOneToOne were alternatives, but MaximumBipartiteMatching is the stated top recommendation from the cluster analysis.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.06\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "tracks_track_duration",\n      "issue": "Low accuracy is mostly structural: sources contain different or extra track durations, and exact list comparison penalizes otherwise plausible unions/preferences.",\n      "fix": "If adjusting, keep a simple source-preference rule rather than union; prefer discogs first based on exact rate evidence: strategy.add_attribute_fuser(\'tracks_track_duration\', favour_sources, source_preferences=[\'discogs\',\'musicbrainz\',\'lastfm\']).",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "The attribute is explicitly marked structurally_limited with ceiling ~64%. union would likely add extras and hurt exact-list evaluation further; intersection would drop true values; prefer_higher_trust is not always available/meaningful for list durations. Since discogs has the best exact rate for duration-related evidence, discogs-first source preference is the least harmful mitigation. Do not spend primary effort here before fixing label, release-date, track-name, and clustering.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.01\n    }\n  ]\n}\n            \n            8b. COMPACT NEXT-PASS SUMMARY:\n            {\n  "root_cause": "The main errors come from fusion/post-clustering configuration, not blocking or matching. Matching F1 is already strong (~0.87\\u20130.90), correspondence files are non-empty, and blocking recall probes found no issues. The dominant failure pattern is missing_fused_value despite matched entities existing, plus wrong source choice in fusion. Current fusion rules contradict the source-vs-validation evidence: label uses most_complete even though only discogs has usable labels; release-date uses prefer_higher_trust with a trust map that incorrectly favors musicbrainz although exact match is 0% for all and discogs has the best fuzzy alignm