   "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "tracks_track_duration": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "tracks_track_position": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      }\n    },\n    "musicbrainz": {\n      "release-date": {\n        "output_type": "datetime",\n        "date_format": "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f",\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "tracks_track_name": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "tracks_track_duration": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "tracks_track_position": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  "llm_list_columns": [\n    "tracks_track_name",\n    "tracks_track_duration",\n    "tracks_track_position"\n  ],\n  "llm_reasoning": "Target style uses full country names, datetime strings formatted like 2003-01-01T00:00:00.000, and duration stored as strings. Discogs has UK abbreviations and date-only/year dates, so normalize country and dates there. MusicBrainz dates are date-only, so convert to target datetime format. Track columns in all sources often contain serialized Python-style lists while target uses actual list values, so mark them as list columns. IDs are preserved and no case transforms are applied because target casing is mixed/preserved.",\n  "datasets": {\n    "discogs": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260323_005631_music/schema-matching/discogs.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260323_005631_music/normalization/attempt_1/discogs.csv",\n      "row_count": 22627,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "release-date": {\n          "output_type": "datetime",\n          "date_format": "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "release-country": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "country_format": "name",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "duration": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_name": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_position": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_duration": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": [\n        "tracks_track_name",\n        "tracks_track_duration",\n        "tracks_track_position"\n      ]\n    },\n    "lastfm": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260323_005631_music/schema-matching/lastfm.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260323_005631_music/normalization/attempt_1/lastfm.csv",\n      "row_count": 9865,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "duration": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_name": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_duration": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_position": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": [\n        "tracks_track_name",\n        "tracks_track_duration",\n        "tracks_track_position"\n      ]\n    },\n    "musicbrainz": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260323_005631_music/schema-matching/musicbrainz.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260323_005631_music/normalization/attempt_1/musicbrainz.csv",\n      "row_count": 4763,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "release-date": {\n          "output_type": "datetime",\n          "date_format": "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%f",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_name": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_duration": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "tracks_track_position": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": [\n        "tracks_track_name",\n        "tracks_track_duration",\n        "tracks_track_position"\n      ]\n    }\n  },\n  "warnings": [],\n  "acceptance_gate": {\n    "requested": false,\n    "request": {},\n    "pending": {}\n  },\n  "reverted_to_original": false,\n  "created_at": "2026-03-23T00:57:20.749148"\n}\n    \n        Create evaluation code that:\n        - Uses the correct fusion strategy\n        - Loads the fused output\n        - Loads the gold standard evaluation set (validation in sealed mode, otherwise test)\n        - Prints structured evaluation metrics\n        - Prints chosen evaluation functions in a compact one-line summary\n        - If helper modules are imported from local files (e.g., list_normalization), use a robust fallback import pattern that works from output/code execution context.\n        - Does NOT require exact matching everywhere by default.\n\n        EVALUATION ROBUSTNESS RULES (MANDATORY):\n- Use validation-set representation as the normalization target for evaluation.\n- Normalize fused and gold columns to the SAME representation before evaluating.\n- For country-like columns: DO NOT call normalize_country or any country normalization function.\n  The pipeline normalization node already ensures fused and gold values use the same country format.\n  Applying normalize_country in evaluation DESTROYS correct matches by converting to a different format.\n  Simply use tokenized_match for country columns, same as other text fields.\n- For free-text/list-like columns, avoid strict exact comparisons unless values are canonical identifiers.\n  Prefer tokenized_match with an explicit threshold (for example 0.7-0.9) instead of exact-only semantics.\n- If using set-based comparison on textual lists, first canonicalize list elements consistently across fused and gold.\n- Choose the right evaluation function per attribute type:\n  * tokenized_match: names, titles, labels, artists, text fields (handles word reordering like "The Beatles" vs "Beatles, The")\n  * year_only_match: dates where only the year matters\n  * set_equality_match: list-like columns (tracks, genres, categories)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: durations, prices, ratings (use reasonable tolerance)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: also use for year/count columns stored as floats (e.g. publish_year, page_count) —\n    cast both fused and gold values to int before comparison to avoid 274.0 != 274 mismatches\n  * exact_match: IDs, codes, boolean fields\n- If the gold set does NOT contain a column (i.e. it is absent or all-null), do NOT evaluate that column.\n  Only evaluate columns that are present and meaningful in BOTH the fused and gold datasets.\n- IMPORTANT: For columns that appear to be nested sub-fields (they share a repeated prefix pattern like\n  "tracks_track_name", "tracks_track_duration", "tracks_track_position"), these are typically derived from\n  XML nested elements and are structurally difficult to evaluate accurately. If such columns consistently\n  show very low accuracy (<20%) in early evaluation attempts, DROP them from evaluation in subsequent\n  attempts — they waste investigation cycles on structural artifacts rather than genuine fusion errors.\n  Focus evaluation on top-level scalar attributes that directly correspond to gold set columns.\n- IMPORTANT: Before evaluation, coerce numeric-like columns (publish_year, page_count, year, count, rating, score)\n  to a consistent type in BOTH fused and gold DataFrames. Common pattern:\n    for col in numeric_cols:\n        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors=\'coerce\')\n        if df[col].dropna().apply(lambda x: float(x).is_integer()).all():\n            df[col] = df[col].astype(\'Int64\')  # nullable int avoids 274.0 vs 274 mismatches\n  This prevents false mismatches from float vs int representation differences.\n- If the fused output contains an "eval_id" column, use fused_id_column="eval_id" (NOT "_id" or "id").\n  The eval_id column is pre-computed to map cluster IDs back to validation-set source IDs.\n        \n            Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The main errors come from fusion/post-clustering configuration, not blocking or matching. Matching F1 is already strong (~0.87\\u20130.90), correspondence files are non-empty, and blocking recall probes found no issues. The dominant failure pattern is missing_fused_value despite matched entities existing, plus wrong source choice in fusion. Current fusion rules contradict the source-vs-validation evidence: label uses most_complete even though only discogs has usable labels; release-date uses prefer_higher_trust with a trust map that incorrectly favors musicbrainz although exact match is 0% for all and discogs has the best fuzzy alignment; track-level fields use favour_sources toward musicbrainz/discogs even though the probe shows track names align best with lastfm. In addition, cluster analysis recommends MaximumBipartiteMatching, suggesting current clustering is allowing bad/ambiguous merges or missed one-to-one resolution that propagate into empty/wrong fused attributes. There is also a normalization issue for track-name casing/list representation, but per routing rules normalization should only be addressed first if the required fix is pre-fusion format transformation. Here, the largest recoverable gains shown by evidence are from choosing the correct resolver/source and post-clustering under frozen correspondences.",\n  "next_node": "pipeline_adaption",\n  "reasoning": "The protected attributes (>85%) should be preserved, so changes should target only weak attributes. Blocking/matching are not the next bottleneck: strong pairwise F1, non-empty correspondence files, and no blocking-recall alarms indicate entity pairs are largely available. The pipeline code shows several fusion misconfigurations directly causing low accuracy: (1) label currently uses most_complete, but source comparison says discogs exact=64%, musicbrainz non_null=0%, so prefer_higher_trust with discogs highest is the correct resolver; (2) release-date currently prefers musicbrainz, yet source comparison recommends voting with discogs > lastfm > musicbrainz, and many fused dates are blank despite source non-null rates of 83\\u2013100%; (3) name/artist/duration trust settings are partially inconsistent with diagnostics; (4) tracks_track_name currently favors musicbrainz, but probe evidence says lastfm exact=77% / fuzzy=100% and shortest_string is recommended; (5) cluster analysis explicitly recommends MaximumBipartiteMatching. These are all fusion/post-clustering fixes within pipeline_adaption. I am preserving already strong attributes and not recommending normalization changes here because pipeline_adaption cannot add preprocessing; the more impactful immediate fix is to correct fusion logic and clustering. After that, if track-name case/list formatting still remains low, normalization can be addressed in a later round.",\n  "ceiling_assessment": "With current source data and frozen matching/imports, overall accuracy appears improvable from 58.4% toward roughly 80\\u201388%. The provided structural ceiling is 91.6%, but tracks_track_duration is structurally limited (ceiling ~64%), and some missing fused values may persist from unmatched singleton/cluster composition issues. Fusion and post-clustering changes alone should recover a substantial share of the 34.2% headroom without risking the 13 protected attributes above 85%.",\n  "recommendations": [\n    {\n      "attribute": "label",\n      "issue": "Current resolver most_complete often returns empty or