g like "The Beatles" vs "Beatles, The")\n  * year_only_match: dates where only the year matters\n  * set_equality_match: list-like columns (tracks, genres, categories)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: durations, prices, ratings (use reasonable tolerance)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: also use for year/count columns stored as floats (e.g. publish_year, page_count) —\n    cast both fused and gold values to int before comparison to avoid 274.0 != 274 mismatches\n  * exact_match: IDs, codes, boolean fields\n- If the gold set does NOT contain a column (i.e. it is absent or all-null), do NOT evaluate that column.\n  Only evaluate columns that are present and meaningful in BOTH the fused and gold datasets.\n- IMPORTANT: For columns that appear to be nested sub-fields (they share a repeated prefix pattern like\n  "tracks_track_name", "tracks_track_duration", "tracks_track_position"), these are typically derived from\n  XML nested elements and are structurally difficult to evaluate accurately. If such columns consistently\n  show very low accuracy (<20%) in early evaluation attempts, DROP them from evaluation in subsequent\n  attempts — they waste investigation cycles on structural artifacts rather than genuine fusion errors.\n  Focus evaluation on top-level scalar attributes that directly correspond to gold set columns.\n- IMPORTANT: Before evaluation, coerce numeric-like columns (publish_year, page_count, year, count, rating, score)\n  to a consistent type in BOTH fused and gold DataFrames. Common pattern:\n    for col in numeric_cols:\n        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors=\'coerce\')\n        if df[col].dropna().apply(lambda x: float(x).is_integer()).all():\n            df[col] = df[col].astype(\'Int64\')  # nullable int avoids 274.0 vs 274 mismatches\n  This prevents false mismatches from float vs int representation differences.\n- If the fused output contains an "eval_id" column, use fused_id_column="eval_id" (NOT "_id" or "id").\n  The eval_id column is pre-computed to map cluster IDs back to validation-set source IDs.\n        \n            Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The main recoverable error is fusion misconfiguration, with one clear regression: release-country fell from 100% to 0% despite source analysis showing musicbrainz is 100% exact and non-null. That pattern indicates the current fusion stage is not preserving the correct source value/format for this attribute. Label and release-date also show fusion-side failures via missing fused values or suboptimal source choice despite matched entities existing. Blocking and matching are not the bottleneck: all correspondence files are populated, blocking recall probes found no issues, and pairwise matching F1 is already strong (~0.87-0.90). Normalization is also not the next fix for the highest-yield issues: release-country was already normalized to full names and validation-aware diagnostics identify the correct source; label is a source-preference problem; release-date missingness is a fusion choice problem. Track-list fields remain mostly structurally limited under exact-list evaluation and should not drive the next iteration.",\n  "next_node": "pipeline_adaption",\n  "reasoning": "Pipeline adaption is the correct next stage because the evidence points to wrong resolver behavior and/or trust/source preference configuration after matching, not missing candidate pairs or source formatting gaps. Protected attributes already above 85%\\u2014including name, artist, and tracks_track_position\\u2014should be preserved. The highest-impact change is to fix release-country resolver behavior to reliably choose musicbrainz, then preserve/strengthen discogs-first trust for label, and keep/enforce MaximumBipartiteMatching due to high ambiguity in correspondence clusters. Release-date can also benefit from a better fusion resolver, but release-country is now the most urgent because it regressed catastrophically 